<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Written Submission from the RSPB</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About the RSPB </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The Royal Society for the Protection of Birds (the RSPB) is the largest wildlife conservation organisation in Europe with over one million members. We believe that sustainability should be at the heart of decision-making. The RSPB’s policy and practical wo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">rk covers a wide range of issues including </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">agriculture</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">water</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">climate change, energy, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">planning  and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">marine issues. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We also manage one of the largest conservation estates in the UK, covering c.143, 000 hectares. Around sixty of our reserves are farmed, co</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">vering more than 20,000 hectares, with around 170 tenant farmers, and 200 employees. We protect and enhance habitats such as lowland farmland, heather moorland, lowland heath, wet grassland, estuaries and reed beds, and our reserves help to protect 63 of t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he 77 most rare or threatened breeding birds in the UK. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Food security is an issue in the UK, not because there is a lack of food</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">but because of poverty and inequality.  In the long-term, food security ultimately depends on maintaining the productive capacity of agriculture and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">is inherently linked to the concept of sustainability. One of the major threats to future food se</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">curity is the unsustainable nature of the current global food system. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Environmental</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> degradation </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">presents a real threat to the UK’s food security because</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> it undermines th</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e UK’s ability to produce food.</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, includin</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">g using resources more efficiently;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">UK (and EU) food security would best be improved by a complete overhaul of the current </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">agriculture and food </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">policy framework</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to ensure its long term sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">A series of high level reports have highlighted the nee</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">d for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">a transition to a more sustainable agricultural model</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The current </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">system</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">receives</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> high levels of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">public </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">support </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">but fails to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> work </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in the public interest</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> Natural Capital Committee recently highlighted that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">natural capital assets are </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in decline at an unprecedented rate</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">hese assets underpin long term productivity. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Urgent a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ction is needed t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">o shift </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> production model on to a more sustainable footing.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Government should build on the findings of the National Ecosystem Assessment and re</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">cognise that agriculture should be appropriate to the natural environment which underpins it</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. F</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ood production is one of a suite of services that society needs from land and we should aim for the optimal balance between </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">this range of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">services</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. F</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ocussing </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">sol</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ely </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> maximum food production</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> jeopardise the natural resources </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">which underpin production</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Although it is clearly important to use resources efficiently to avoid waste, when </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">determining the best approach to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">secure long term production </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">targets</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> efficiency must </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">not be the primary driver. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">fficiency – based on extreme specialisation – </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">can result in decreased</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> resilience</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> within the farming system</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Instead the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> overarching aim must b</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to achieve sustainable food production to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">long term f</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ood </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">production</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">An approach which considers only the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> of certain elements of the system could result in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">approaches</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> fundamentally unsustainable in the long term</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> fail to make best use of the land in a given area</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> deliver the greatest benefit for society</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and indeed could be more susceptible to failure </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">due to a lack of resilience</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">(see discussion below)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">There is no </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">single </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">correct approach to more sustainable agricultural system. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Farms should ensure that the levels a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">nd type of production respect and operate within environmental limits, recognising and responding to the particular tensions with environment that exist in its location.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> There are a number of considerations which can help guide decisions. Any </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">farm</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">which is</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> seeking to be sustainable should aim to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> enhance soil quality</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> protect and enhance carbon stores</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">enhance </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">sustain </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">wildlife</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> utilise a variety of crop types and livestock breeds to maintain genetic diversity</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> minimise direct and indirect Greenhouse gas</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> (GHG) emissions </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in total terms and not just per unit of output including carbon sequestration and storage impacts</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, eliminate pollution</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and adverse impacts on the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">water environment</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and not compromise the ability of other countries to manage their own lan</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">d sustainably.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">A consideration of all these </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">elements </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">undoubtedly</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> adds to the complexity of the task but will also ensure</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> that we are investing in approaches which secure our natural resources and food security in the longer term</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In addition to improving the sustainability of production </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">re is a need to encourage the uptake of a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> more sustainable diet to make the best use of land and tackle the epidemic of diet related illness which afflicts those on western</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> style </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">diets</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">character</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ise</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> by high intakes of red meat and dairy</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, sugary and high-fat foods, refined grains </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">processed meat</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The predicted rise in demand for food – potentially doubling by 2050 - comes not primarily from increasing populations</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> but</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> from changing diets. The r</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ise of the middle classes </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in countries such as </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">China and India will result in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">a demand for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">diets richer in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">meat putting increased demand on the global food system</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ensure that the UK is leading the way in demonstrating integrated policy which recognise</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">s the importance of sustainable consumption as part of solution to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">food security g</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">overnment</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> must take action to facilitate the uptake of more sustainable dietary choices.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> The recent green food project developed a set of principles for a sustainable diet</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> which should be developed and communicated to highlight the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> importance of changing our diets for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">society’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> health and that of the environment.  </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">If we are to achieve a sustainable fo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">od and farming system it is important that the price of food accurately reflects the costs of producing it</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and any public subsidies are </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">transparent and clear in their aims</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. The negative externalities of unsustainable production systems should be reflected </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in the price of food</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> rather than being paid for elsewhere</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Alongside a robust regulatory baseline t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">his </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> benefit sustainable producers</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> improv</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> our long term food security, increas</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> resilience through more diversity in farming systems and reduc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the lik</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">elihood of extreme price fluctuations.  For example, the reliance of intensive livestock production in the UK on imported protein means these systems lack resilience and are vulnerable to increases in input prices</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">There</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> is insufficient transparency and clarity about where the money goes to in the food and farming system, both in terms of money paid at the till and public funding</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and the impacts on the health of our </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">countryside. The</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> complexity of the Common Agricultural Policy </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">a barrier to understanding of the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">impact of this</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> policy </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">on the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> environment, while lack of transparency in the food supply chain makes choosing sustainable options difficult. The public’s ability to discrimin</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ate between options in order to support more sustainable producers is made difficult</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The result of this is that the most</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> sustainable  farmers are </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">disadvantaged</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">There needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">much greater transparency, awareness and accountability </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">within the food sys</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">tem to correct this imbalance.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">There is often a lack of clarity over </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">where </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">consumers </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">money goes </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in the food supply chain. An organic lamb can be sold in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">major</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> retailers at £13.98/kg, but the farmer who produced it on the hills of a National Park, usin</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">g no inputs and extensively reared, receives only £1.98/kg, often </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the same as </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">non-organic </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">producers</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> higher input systems. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">reater transparency within the food </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">system is needed </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">enable the public to better understand where their money is going by creating</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> clear lines of accountability between producers, processors, retailers, shoppers and taxpayers. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">This would provide clarity on which sectors get most 'value-added' down the food chain, and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">help ensure that a fair share of the cost of food</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> flow</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to the most</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> sustainable primary growers and farmers.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">There is no shortage of food in the UK today but there are people who are unable to eat a good diet as they are unable to afford it or access it. Producing more food at the expense of our environments health and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">potentially public health, is not a solution to this problem. The Marmot review</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> into social-related health inequalities in England, ‘Fair Society, Healthy Lives’, sets out a framework for action to ensure social justice, health and sustainability are at t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he heart of all policies. Recommendations include promoting sustainable local communities, access to good quality green space and sustainable food production.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The implications of volatility in global food supply and demand for UK food security;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Government </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">statistics show that the UK is over 60% self-sufficient in food (or over 70% if you consider only the foods that can actually be grown here). By comparison, we were less than 50% self sufficient for much of the 1930s, 40s, and 50s. So although </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the UK is</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> mo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">re self reliant than </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">it was </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">we are still part of the global market and as such will be subject to the fluctuations which exist. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The UK can play a role in helping to reduce </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the impact of these fluctuations </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">by developing a more sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and resilient </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">appr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">oach to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">our domestic agricultural system and so reducing our reliance on imported </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">feedstocks</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and the exposure of our food and farming systems to ext</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ernal shocks, be they economic, physical or </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">environmental</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The UK should play a leading role in the interna</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">tional policy debate to eliminate harmful policies such as those which result in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">biofuels</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> driving up commodity prices.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">uture volatility will be connected to extreme weather events or shifts in growing conditions linked to climate change. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Therefore f</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ood </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">security policies will be increasingly </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">dependant</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> on international action to secure a global deal limiting dangerous climate change, and on domestic action to ensure sustainable adaptation to new climate conditions for agriculture in the UK.</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The potential v</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">alue and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food security.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Science has an important role to play in developing a more sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and resilient </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">agricultural system</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to ensure future UK food security</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The UK could take a leading role in developi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ng new models of sustainable agriculture which meet the need to produce enough to feed a growing population within environmental limits. In order to achieve this r</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">esearch must take a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">broad</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> perspective and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">fully address </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the environmental impacts as well as </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the agronomic.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Currently there is an issue that research is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">siloed</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and as such fails to take account of the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">multifunctional nature of agriculture. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Research should focus on </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">sustainable production methods which address both farm</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">farming </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">system and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">landscape</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> levels.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> It is vital that the use of any technology does not lead to further narrowing of the range of crops grown: diversity is key to ensuring resilience in the face of unpredictable change.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">With regard to GM technology there may be potential f</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">or GM crops which contribute to a more sustainable agricultural system however this has not been the focus of developments to date, indeed the predominant GM crops are those which facilitate the use of agr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">chemicals </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">which can damage soil </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and do not encoura</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ge integrated pest control. In </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">developing and implementing new research</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the following</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> considerations should be taken into account:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Its effects on biodiversity, including indirect impacts through changes to farming practices. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Gene flow and its consequences</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Selection for herbicide-tolerant weeds. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Persistence, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">weediness</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and invasiveness of the GMO itself. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The cumulative risk from this GMO alongside other factors. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Effects on soil function. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Human health impacts, including </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">direct</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> exposure</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">nutritional chan</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ges</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, presence</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> of allergens.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Its relative environmental impact compared with alternative approaches </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Access to research materials to allow independent assessment. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">mpirical monitoring of the environmental, human and animal health and agronomic impacts. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">tringent traceability and accurate labelling rules.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 82.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> cost from the escape of genes from GM crops should be borne by the ‘contaminator’ and not those ‘contaminated’ - i.e. the polluter pays</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">There is a need to improve the dissemination of research </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">findings through effective knowledge transfer systems to ensure that reaches farmers and to allow them to adapt their farming systems accordingly.</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability, can contribute to increased res</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ilience;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The horsemeat scandal at the start of this year highlighted </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the importan</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ce</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> of t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ransparen</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">cy within </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">supply cha</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ins, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and the need for effective oversight. The ability to trace the provenance of food is key </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">both to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">maintain</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> consumer trust</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and u</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">nderstand</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the environmental impact of a product</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Shorter more </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">transparent food</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> chain</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">s are</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> essential </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">develop a better understanding of where the money goes within the food system for a range of products</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> as discussed above</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Shorter supply chains would </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">help enhance traceability and build trust, but also to allow environmentally friendly farming to be supported via more direct connections to markets.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">A better understanding of the true costs of production can help improve resilience in its broadest sense, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">through a better understanding of the weaknesses in the system. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">A more detailed exploration of the importance of resilience is given below.</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In the UK clim</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ate change is predicted to result in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">increased temperatures and increased rainfall extremes, however it is not clear what this will mean for crop yields</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">t is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">expected </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> remain food secure over the next 40 years</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Building resilience </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">to the farming sector will be an important strategy to minimise both economic and output losses </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">due to extreme weather events</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">here is no consensus</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> on a definition of resilience</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> – the ability to absorb shock and, in some definitions the ability to change</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> or reorganise as a response to such a shock</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> is often cited</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">has been described</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> as the ability of social-ecological system</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">s,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> both to withstand perturbations from</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> for instance</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> climate or economic shocks</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and to rebuild and renew itself afterwards. Loss</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> of resilience can cause loss of valuable ecosystem services</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">6.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Society and institutions often find it difficult to shift to more resilient models</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">re are many reasons for this</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he fact we work in hierarchies and silos</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">may make </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">it difficult to understand the interconnections </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and potential benefits of different approaches.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In agriculture, t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">use of monocultures where diversity is denied in the pursuit of economies of scale </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">can make change difficult</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Another reason is the attract</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ion </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">of focusing</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> on efficiency and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">short term profit maximisation, this increases </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the risk that economic models quickly buckle when stress is applied.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> Finally a failure</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to invest in appropriate infrastructure to underpin more resilient models</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> can present a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> obstacle</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">6.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In order to overcome these issues we need to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">accept </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the complexity of systems and rather than seek to oversimplify them</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">better recognise the multiple benefits which are </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">delivered by </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">such </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">systems</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">  e.g. sustaining </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">bio</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">diversity, living within ec</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ological boundaries</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> generating social capital. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">6.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">For example </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">UK agriculture’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">increasing specialisation into specific farming types, contraction of crop rotations, increased stocking density and reduction of genetic diversity have all had profound envi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ronmental impacts. They have also made the system more brittle in that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Farmers are ever more reliant on a range of chemicals whose utility reduces as pests become resistant, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Disease transmission is increased with less likelihood of inherited resistance</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Volatility in input prices can wipe out profit margins for farmers</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 10pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Soil and water condition suffers </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">due to lack of rotations and nutrient build up.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">6.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">One approach to address these problems is to look for down</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">stream fixes </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">build</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ing new</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> reservoirs and develop new pesticides and drugs. While </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">such actions can be useful</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> a more cost effective approach may</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">be to seek to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">address the fundamental risk of failure which could have devastating consequences in a highly specialised agricultural syst</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">em.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> B</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">uilding resilience through seeking alternative environmentally sustainable approaches</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> such as by</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> extending crop rotations, us</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ing integrated pest management and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">introducing traditional bre</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">eds less reliant on inputs although more complex, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">can </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">deliver a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> wider range of beneficial outcomes and reduce the potential impacts of extreme weather events</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">6.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Investment in ever more efficient approaches without a proper assessment of alternative approaches can result in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">sector</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> becoming ‘locked in’ to unsustainable a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">pproaches and therefore being unable to deliver a broader range of benefit to society.</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new markets; </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In the short term in the UK w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e don’t need to increa</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">se production</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> we need to make it more sustainable</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> – environmentally, economically and socially</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Simply pursuing increased production does not necessarily result in increased profit and is not good for farmers, society or the environment</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">What is vital is creating value - for society and for farm businesses </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in sustainable ways. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Food is not the only output from our agricultural </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">system;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">there are a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> range of other services that matter to us all, such as water quality, carbon storage, flood a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">lleviation, the landscape, recreation,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> employment, high</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> animal welfare and wildlife</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> habitats</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. But the market often fails to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">distinguish between those </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">providing these wider benefits to society, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and those who are not. Often farmers seeking to be more sustain</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">able are unable </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> compete with those farming in a less sustainable way.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">£</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">3bn </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">public funding for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">agriculture via t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he Common Agricultural Policy should be </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">supporting farmers to become more sustainable and rewarding them for the wider public goods the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">y produce</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. But only a tiny proportion of this expenditure represents good value for the public purse by being targeted to sustainable farmers. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Increasing agricultural specialisation, driven by a narrow focus on efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> has resulted in polarisation </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">of production and the loss of mixed, rotational farming that has underpinned good soil, crop and animal husbandry for centuries. Historically farms </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">utilised</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> rotations which build soil and circulate nutrients. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Mixed farms</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> now find it difficult to compete wi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">th the extremely specialised arable and livestock systems as the benefits of mixed systems and the externalities (soil degradation, feed and nutrient imports) of intensive systems</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> are not reflected in our current economic model</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. This specialisation, conc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">entration on just a few major commodity crops and reliance on imported protein (the EU is already reliant on importing three-quarters of protein-rich feed) has left limited diversity, which combined with increasingly unpredictable extremes of weather, leav</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">es food production vulnerable and lacking resilience.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">7.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Understanding and encouraging such complexity in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">farming </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">sector </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">relies on skilled advisors. Too often the provision of advice is now left to those with vested interests and narrow specialities. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In o</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">rder to support the shift to a more sustainable agricultural system a well informed, impartial advisory network is required.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">7.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">This shift </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">be underpinned by the infrastructure required for mixed, sustainable agriculture systems such as more small and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> medium sized abattoirs, to enable shorter chains and trustworthy traceability.</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 14.07pt; padding-left:3.93pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ways of increasing self sufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Within this submission we have referred to a number of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">actions</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> we believe are requ</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ired to support a thriving UK agricultural system. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">These </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">include better direction of support payments, investment in skills</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> training </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and advisory support </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">to better equip the industry </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">to pursue </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">a more sustainable approach and investment in infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to underpin this shift. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 10pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">A change in peoples eating habits to more sustainable diets as described above would also improve our self sufficiency. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">However reducing use of cereals and oilseeds in animal feed through less intensive livestock farming could mak</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the UK</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> more self-sufficient in these crops and would reduce reliance on imported protein. More sustainable diets would also benefit UK horticulture</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> through increased demand for vegetables</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Foresight future of food </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">http://www.bis.gov.uk/assets/foresight/docs/food-and-farming/11-546-future-of-food-and-farming-report.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p s